# Client imports — stay out of `services/` and `db/`

Client components (`"use client"` files) run in the browser bundle. Modules under `@/services/*` and `@/db/*` import `next/headers`, `cookies()`, `auth`, and the DB driver, which are not allowed in client code. If a client file imports a **runtime value** from those paths, Next.js will fail the build with:

> You're importing a module that depends on "next/headers". This API is only available in Server Components…

## The layered convention this codebase uses

| Layer | Who may import from it? | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `@/services/*` | server components, server actions, API routes only | Reads session / tenant / DB |
| `@/actions/*` (`"use server"`) | server **and** client components | Narrow bridge that wraps service calls |
| `@/hooks/use-*` | client components | React Query wrappers around actions |
| `@/lib/*` | anyone | Pure utilities with **zero** server imports |

## Rules for client files (`"use client"` or `components/**/*.tsx`)

- Runtime values must come from `@/hooks/*`, `@/actions/*`, `@/components/*`, or `@/lib/*`.
- Types from `@/services/*` and `@/db/*` are fine, but **only** via `import type { ... }` — `import type` is erased at build time, so it never drags server modules into the client bundle.
- If a pure helper is needed by both server and client (e.g. money math, label maps), put it in `@/lib/*` and re-export from the service if server callers want the same symbol.
- If a server operation is needed from the client, expose it as an action in `@/actions/*` and consume it via a hook in `@/hooks/*`. Do **not** call the service directly.

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — value import of a server module
import { computePaymentSummary, getSupplierInvoices } from "@/services/receiving";

// ❌ BAD — plain import of a type (also pulls the module in older TS configs)
import { SalesOrderDetail } from "@/services/orders";

// ✅ GOOD — pure helper from lib
import { computePaymentSummary } from "@/lib/supplier-invoices/payment-summary";

// ✅ GOOD — type-only import, erased at build time
import type { SalesOrderDetail } from "@/services/orders";

// ✅ GOOD — server data through the action/hook bridge
import { useCurrentPortalUser } from "@/hooks/use-current-portal-user";
import { getCurrentPortalUserAction } from "@/actions/users"; // when calling directly from a form submit, etc.
```

## When a value is pure, prefer `@/lib/*` over a server action

Server actions incur a network roundtrip. Do not wrap pure math / formatters / constants in an action just to import them from the client — move them to `@/lib/*` and import directly from both sides.
